        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral SPI1",
        "description": "Read SPI1 peripheral registers to check BUSY flag in status register"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "**No \u2014 the SPI1 BUSY flag is not stuck.**\n\nHere's the full picture from the live SR snapshot:\n\n| SR Field | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **BSY** | **0** | \u2705 Not busy \u2014 peripheral is idle |\n| TXE | 0 | TX buffer not empty (but SPE=0, so irrelevant) |\n| RXNE | 0 | No unread data in RX buffer |\n| OVR | 0 | No overrun error |\n| MODF | 0 | No mode fault |\n| CRCERR | 0 | No CRC error |\n| TIFRFE | 0 | No TI frame format error |\n| FRLVL | 0 | RX FIFO empty |\n| FTLVL | 0 | TX FIFO empty |\n\n**SR raw value = 0x00000000** \u2014 the entire status register is clear.\n\nWorth noting: **CR1.SPE = 0**, meaning SPI1 isn't even enabled right now, so BSY being 0 is fully expected. If you suspected a stuck-busy scenario (e.g. after a failed transfer), you'd want to re-check with SPE=1 during an active transaction \u2014 or look for a prior OVR/MODF that froze the state machine before the peripheral was disabled."
}